abstract: There is a widely prevalent impression, in regard to Irish and Scotch surnames, that the Mao is distinctively Scottish and the O' distinctively Irish, and that both prefixes signify son. This is an error. In Gaelic, the national language both of Ireland and Scotland since the dawn of history, Mac (incorrectly written Mc and M') signifies son, and O' (Gaelic form Ua) grandson or descendant.
